**_This post is part of our special coverage[Japan Earthquake
2011](https://globalvoicesonline.org/specialcoverage/japan-earthquake-
tsunami-2011/)._**

It's human nature for rumors to run rampant in a high pressure situation, and
social meda tools can be a double-edged sword in expediting this situation.
Yasuhisa Hasegawa gives an analysis in his blog post “The Light and Darkness
of Social Media” ([ソーシャルメディアがもつ光と闇](http://www.yasuhisa.com/could/diary/light-
and-darkness/)), drawing parallels between social media usage and consumption
of mass media.

Hasegawa is a widely respected Web designer, developer, and consultant in
Tokyo. He tweets in Japanese at [@yhassy](http://www.twitter.com/yhassy).

The following post was translated in its entirety under the terms of [CC BY-
NC-SA 2.1](http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/2.1/jp/).

Social media played a great role during the revolution in Egypt at the
beginning of this year. Now more than ever, people are calling to leverage
social media for public/social activities.

